------------------------------------

	BASICS

- To make comments use %

- Shortcut for comment: 

	[ctrl] + /			(on Kile)
	[ctrl] + T			(on TeXstudio)




- A LaTeX file starts by defining the Class of document.
- Different Classes of Documents have different commands and properties.

- Define Class of the Document:

\documentclass[<option>, ..., <option>]{<class>}


classes:
		article
		book
		report
		letter
		...

options:
		<number>pt		Font size (default= 10)
		
		onecolumn		(default)
		twocolumn
		
		oneside			(pages, default for ´article´ and ´report´)
		twoside			(pages, default for ´book´)
		
		titlepage		(default for ´book´ and ´report´)
		notitlepage		(default for ´article´)
		
		openright		Chapters on new right page (default for ´book´)
		openany			Chapters on any new page (default for ´report´)
		
		letterpaper		(default)
		a4paper
		a5paper
		b5paper
		legalpaper
		executivepaper
		...




- Begin and End Document.
- This is where all the document content goes.
- Some commands here are available for all Classes of Documents, some are exclusive to some Classes.


\begin{document}

	<content>

\end{document}


------------------------------------

	PACKAGES


- Use a package:

\usepackage[<options>][<package>]


- Some useful packages:

% Change language of automatic text to pt-br (eg. chapters, sections):
\usepackage[brazil]{babel}

% Proper read of accentuation and cedilla on the input file:
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
% OR if using a encoding other than utf-8:
\usepackage[latin1]{inputenc}

% Proper mapping of accentuation and cedilla to the output document:
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}

% Use the Latin Moder font:
\usepackage{lmodern}

------------------------------------

	CONFIGURATIONS

- Commands have main parameters in braces ´{ }´ and optional parameters in brackets ´[ ]´.



- Input a Tex file (only processes the file):

\input{<tex-file>}


- Include a Tex file (generates file´s pages):

\include{<tex-file>}




NUMBERING


- To suppress page numbering:

\pagenumbering{gobble}


- To switch on page numbering with Arabic Numbers:

\pagenumbering{arabic}


- To switch on page numbering with Roman Numbers:

\pagenumbering{roman}
\pagenumbering{Roman}


- To switch on page numbering with Letters:

\pagenumbering{alph}
\pagenumbering{Alph}


- Set till which depth of sections are numbered:

\setcounter{secnumdepth}{<number>}

number=
		0		- Chapter
		1		- Section
		2		- Subsection (default)
		3		- Subsubsection
		4		- Paragraph
		5		- Subparagraph


- Set till which depth of sections are included on the Table of Contents:

\setcounter{tocdepth}{<number>}





HYPHENATION

- Teach LaTeX how to hyphenate a word or to never hyphenate it:

\hyphenation{ hy-phe-na-te }
\hyphenation{ neverHyphenate }

\hyphenation{ hy-phe-na-te neverHyphenate }




------------------------------------

	ANY CLASS ( DOCUMENT CONTENTS )



SECTIONING

- LaTex numbers Sections, Subsections, Chapters, Parts, etc, automatically.


- Create new Section, Subsections and Subsubsections:

\section{<title>}
\subsection{<title>}
\subsubsection{<title>}


- Create unnumbered Sections:

\section*{<title>}
\subsection*{<title>}
\subsubsection*{<title>}


- Create titled Paragraphs and Subparagraphs:

\paragraph{<title>}
\subparagraph{<title>}





PARAGRAPH IDENTATION

- For LaTeX to separate paragraphs, make an empty line between then.

- Make the next paragraph NOT be indented:

\noindent


- Or just give a new line at the end of the previous paragraph with:
- (it is always wrong to have a blank line after ´\\´)

\\
\newline


- To indent the very first line after a new Section use the package:

\usepackage{indentfirst}


- To get the text to a new page:

\newpage




------------------------------------

	TITLE & TABLE OF CONTENTS

- Define Author:

\author{<name>}


- Define Title of the Document:

\title{<title>}


- Define the Date:

\date{<text>}
\date{\today}
\date{}				% blank date



- Generate Title:

\maketitle



- Generate Table of Contents:

\tableofcontents



------------------------------------

	LISTS

- To create unordered List use the ´itemize´ environment and put the ´item´s inside:

\begin{itemize}
  \item <text>
  \item <text>
  ...
\end{itemize}


- To create unordered List use the ´enumerate´ environment and put the ´item´s inside:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item <text>
  \item <text>
  ...
\end{enumerate}



- Nested Lists:
- You can insert a list inside another list.
- Including mixed types.

\begin{enumerate}
  \item <text>
  \item <text>
  \begin{enumerate}
    \item <text>
    \item <text>
    ...
  \end{enumerate}
  ...
\end{enumerate}



------------------------------------

	SYMBOLS


- Reserverd Symbols:

	%, $, &, #, _, {, }

- To include reserverd symbols on the text they need to be preceded by the escape character ´\´:

	\%, \$, \&, \#, \_, \{, \}




- To open quotes use back ` or ``
- To close quotes use apostrophe ' or ''



- Type of dashes:

	-				hyphen
	--				simple dash
	---				indent
	$-<number>$		minus sign (or )



- Ellipsis ´...´:

\dots



- Write today´s date:

\today



- Write the LaTeX stylized thingy:

\LaTeX





------------------------------------

	BASIC FORMATING


- Bold:

\textbf{<text>}

	[alt] + [shift] + B		(on Kile)
	[ctrl] + B				(on TeXstudio)


- Italic:

\textit{<text>}

	[alt] + [shift] + I		(on Kile)
	[ctrl] + I				(on TeXstudio)


- Underline:

\undeline{<text>}


- Emphasis:

\emph{<text>}





- Some Fonts:

\textrm{<text>}				% Romman Font
\textsf{<text>}				% Sans Serif
\texttt{<text>}				% Type Writer (good for code)
\textsc{<text>}				% Small Caps


- Font sizes:

\tiny{<text>}
\scriptsize{<text>}
\footnotesize{<text>}
\small{<text>}
\normalize{<text>}
\large{<text>}
\Large{<text>}
\LARGE{<text>}
\huge{<text>}
\Huge{<text>}




- Align left (default):

\begin{flushleft}
	<text>
\end{flushleft}


- Centralize:

\begin{center}
	<text>
\end{center}


- Align right:

\begin{flushright}
	<text>
\end{flushright}



DIFFERENT FONT SIZES

- On TeXstudio:  selecte Text -> Latex -> Font Size






------------------------------------

	MATH

- LaTeX Mathematics Wiki:

url: (https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX/Mathematics)



- Many commands in this section use the package ´amsmath´ and, for the fonts section, ´amssymb´:

\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{amssymb}



- The way Equations are displayed depends on the delimiters (that are not rendered).
- Also, all the commands in this section are specific for within Equations.
- You CANNOT use empty lines within Equations.
- Use only one Equation per environment.

	% In-line Equations:
	\(    \)
	 $     $
	\begin{math}    \end{math}

	% Displayed Equations:
	\[    \]
	$$    $$
	\begin{equation*}    \end{equation*}
	\begin{displaymath}    \end{displaymath}

	% Displayed Numbered Equations:
	\begin{equation}    \end{equation}


- To add a text inside a equation:

\text{ <text> }
\textrm{ <text> }     % roman font family
\textit{ <text> }
\textbf{ <text> }


- To add space inside a Equation (ascending order):

\!        % less than the default
\,
\:
\;
\         % equel to space in normal text (space after the backslash!)
\quad     % equal to the current font size
\qquad    % twice of \quad


- Parentheses and brackets on Equations can be directly typed.
- Pipes ´| |´ can also be typed directly.
- Double pipes ´|| ||´ and Braces ´{ }´ need to be escaped.
- Angle brackets ´⟨ ⟩´ have the command ´langle´.

(    )                  % (    )
[    ]                  % [    ]
|    |                  % |    |
\|    \|                % ||   ||
\{    \}                % {    }
\langle    \langle      % ⟨    ⟩


- To add parentheses and brackets resized dynamically use:

\left(    \right)
\left[    \right]


- To add parentheses and brackets resized dynamically use:

url: (https://www.overleaf.com/learn/latex/Brackets_and_Parentheses#Reference_guide)


- To write Subscript and Superscrip (eg. exponents):

<base>_<subscript>
<base>_{ <subscript> }

<base>^<superscrip>
<base>^{ <superscrip> }

<base>_{ <subscript> }^{ <superscrip> }


- To write fractions:

\frac{ <numerator> }{ <denominator> }
\tfrac{ <numerator> }{ <denominator> }
^<numerator>/_<denominator>


- To write a Integral:

\int_{ <lower> }^{ <upper> }  <equation>  \,dx


- To write double/triple Integrals:

\int_{ <lower> }  <equation>  \,du
\iint_{ <lower> }  <equation>  \,du\,dv
\iiint_{ <lower> }  <equation>  \,du\,dv\,dw


- To write close line/surface Integrals:

\oint_{ <lower> }  <equation>  \,ds


- To write Sums and Products:

\sum_{ <lower> }^{ <upper> }  <equation>
\prod_{ <lower> }^{ <upper> }  <equation>


- To write Limits:

\lim_{ <variable> \to <value> }  <equation>









HATS AND ACCENTS

- To add a hat to a letter in text-mode:

\^{ <letter> }


- To add a hat to a letter in math-mode (equation):

\hat{ <letter> }
\widehat{ <letter> }
\overrightarrow{ <lettersss> }


- To write a vector (arrow above):

\vec{ <letter> }


- To write a vector with superscrip (that doesn´t look crap):

\vec{ <letter> }^{ \, <superscrip> }


- Misc (ye, I´m lazy):

\dot{x}        % .
\ddot{x}       % ..
\acute{x}      % ´
\grave{x}      % `
\bar{x}        % -
\tilde{x}      % ~
\check{x}      % v
\breve{x}      % V








MULTIPLE EQUATIONS

- To align parts of different Equations use the package ´amsmath´:

\usepackage{amsmath}


- If you just need to display consecutive Equations, centered, use the ´gather´ environment.
- The double backslash ´\\´ works as a newline character.

\begin{gather}
<equation> \\
<equation> \\
...
\end{gather}

\begin{gather*}
<equation> \\
<equation> \\
...
\end{gather*}


- To align a certain point of the Equations use the ´align´ environment.
- Use the ampersand ´&´, to set the vertical align points.

\begin{align}
<pieces> & = <pieces> \\
<pieces> & = <pieces> \\
...
\end{align}

\begin{align*}
<pieces> & = <pieces> \\
<pieces> & = <pieces> \\
...
\end{align*}

\begin{align}
<pieces> & = <pieces>      &  <pieces> & = <pieces> \\
<pieces> & = <pieces>      &  <pieces> & = <pieces> \\
...
\end{align}


- To split a single Equations into smaller pieces, that will be aligned use the ´multline´ environment:

\begin{multline}
<pieces> = & <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
...
\end{multline}

\begin{multline*}
<pieces> = & <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
...
\end{multline*}


- To split a single Equations, within the ´equation´ environment, use the ´split´ environment:

\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
<pieces> = & <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
& <pieces> \\
...
\end{split}
\end{equation}




CASE DEFINITION

\begin{equation}
<pieces> = 
\begin{cases}
<pieces>,    & <condition> \\
<pieces>,    & <condition> \\
<pieces>,    & <condition> \\
...
\end{cases}
\end{equation}







CROSSED REFERENCE

- Create a Label that can be referenced.
- Place it inside Displayed Numbered Equations.

\begin{equation} \label{ <label> }
<equation>
\end{equation}



- Reference the Section number:

\ref{ <label> }







MATH FONTS

- Package ´amssymb´ or ´amsfonts´:

\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsfonts}


- To make Mathematical Symbols Bold:

\pmb{ <math> }
\boldsymbol{ <math> }


- Capital letters-only font typefaces:

\mathcal{ <letters> }     % Calligraphic (curly)
\mathfrak{ <letters> }    % Fraktur (MORE curly)
\mathbb{ <letters> }      % Blackboard bold (those letters for sets)






